# Point to the CSV once
csv_file = "/home/dias-benchmarks/notebooks/saisandeepjallepalli/adidas-retail-eda-data-visualization/input/adidas-us-retail-products-dataset/adidas.csv"

# 1) Load a small sample on GPU to infer dtypes (much cheaper than full-file inference)
sample_df = pd.read_csv(csv_file, nrows=1000)
dtype_map = sample_df.dtypes.to_dict()

# 2) Read the full CSV on GPU with explicit dtypes
#    - memory_map=True lets the GPU reader map the file into GPU address space
#    - low_memory=False disables row-chunking in the parser
# This avoids unsupported 'blocksize' and keeps everything on the GPU

df = pd.read_csv(
    csv_file,
    dtype=dtype_map,
    memory_map=True,
    low_memory=False
)
Reason: Removed the unsupported `blocksize` argument (it isn’t part of the pandas-API surface exposed by cudf.pandas). Instead, keep the dtype inference via a small 1k-row sample and pass that mapping into the full-file read. Added memory_map=True to let cudf map the file directly into GPU memory, and low_memory=False to avoid internal row-chunking—all of which keeps the work on the GPU and avoids CPU/GPU round trips.
